msgid "Installing on Linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:6
msgid ""
"Check the :doc:`minimum requirements and where to get Blender "
"</getting_started/installing_blender/installing>`, if you haven't done so "
"yet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:11
msgid "Specific packages for distributions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:13
msgid ""
"Some Linux distributions may have on their repositories a specific package "
"for Blender."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:15
msgid ""
"Installing Blender via the distribution's native mechanisms ensures "
"consistency with other packages on the system and may provide other features"
" (given by the package manager), such as listing of packages, update "
"notifications and automatic menu configuration. Be aware, though, that the "
"package may be outdated comparing to the latest official release, or not "
"include some features of Blender. For example, some distributions do not "
"build Blender with CUDA support for licensing reasons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:21
msgid ""
"If there is a specific package for your distribution, you may choose what is"
" preferable and most convenient, otherwise there is nothing wrong with the "
"official binary on `blender.org <http://www.blender.org/download/>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:26
msgid "Download from blender.org"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:28
msgid ""
"Download the Linux version for your architecture and uncompress the file to "
"the desired location (eg. ~/software or /usr/local)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:31
msgid "Blender can now be launched by double-clicking the executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:34
msgid ""
"For easy access, you can configure your system by adding a menu entry or "
"shortcut for Blender and associate and open ``.blend`` files with Blender "
"when opening from the file browser. These settings typically belong to the "
"Window Manager (KDE, Gnome, Unity)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:40
msgid "Running from the terminal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:42
msgid ""
"To run Blender from the terminal without needing to be in the executable "
"directory, add the extracted folder to the environment PATH."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:45
msgid ""
"Add the following command to .bash_rc or .bash_profile with Blender's "
"binary:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:54
msgid ""
"If you use daily builds and update Blender frequently, you can link or "
"always rename your folder to 'blender' and use this name for the ``PATH`` "
"environment variable and for keeping the window manager menu up to date."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:60
msgid "Avoiding Alt+Mouse Conflict"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:62
msgid ""
"Many Window Managers default to :kbd:`Alt-LMB` for moving windows, which is "
"a shortcut that Blender uses to simulate a 3 button mouse. You can either "
"have this feature disabled :menuselection:`User Preferences --> Input --> "
"Emulate 3 Button Mouse` or you can change the Window Manager settings to use"
" the *Meta* key instead (also called *Super* or *Windows key*):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/getting_started/installing_blender/linux.rst:68
msgid ""
"**KDE:** System Settings > Window Behavior > Window Behavior > Window "
"Actions , Switch 'Alt' for 'Meta' key"
msgstr ""

